3NzH4PqCxzthHo72jP7sPzJqy4ce-kl4FpZYRJuKh-d6l2YhEn9k=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test fixture structure**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether to create a separate public test fixture file, keeping in mind the requirement for a one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and generated test class files. It seems like adding an extra fixture file might go against this rule. Each dynamic-access class should be covered in a dedicated Java test file, but I wonder if including a package-private top-level fixture in the same file would work. However, all top-level test classes must be public, so I’m debating if a fixture could be considered a test or not.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating static classes in tests**\\n\\nI'm considering how to restructure the TestClassScannerTest. It looks like the nested static class might be difficult to extend. I think I could skip the superclass and focus on just getting the declared classes at the call site. The source comments mention the superclass, but perhaps it isn't necessary to cover both. I believe I can simplify the test assertion and increase behavior by using the top-level base. I’ll need to edit the file to implement these changes.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_BmK4Xty9BJrHhvZMvr9S27GB|fc_0dae95c566a243cc016a28e724205c81969c8489e3facd3422", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/src/test/java/org_springframework/spring_test/TestClassScannerTest.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 8010, "output": 1375, "cacheRead": 25600, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 34985, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1781065477636, "responseId": "resp_0dae95c566a243cc016a28e70656c08196b443770d83b43cf2"}}
